result.execSummary:
The defendant Joshua Michael Lieblein was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Bail Jumping-Felony [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse], a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(b).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: Successfully complete "Batterers intervention" counseling and continue programming. Attend and complete parenting classes. Successfully complete any other counseling and/or treatment deemed appropriate.
Defendant to participate in Alcohol and Drug Assessment and successfully complete recommended treatment. Random urine screens and breathalyzer test.

Maintain absolute sobriety.  No drugs.  No alcohol. No contact with victim, Phillis C., without court approval.  Defendant may have contact with the victim through a third party to arrange time with children.
Obtain GED/HSED. Obtain and maintain employment.

Defendant shall provide a DNA sample for the Data Bank and pay all appropriate costs. Defendant to pay all applicable costs and surcharges, victim/witness surcharge, the domestic violence surcharge, and supervision fees as determined by the Department of Corrections, during period of probation or CIVIL JUDGMENT to issue.  (Also applies to costs in case 2013CF5079. Court ordered that the $350.00 cash bail on deposit in case 2013CF5079 should be paid to victim, Phillis C., for restitution.)

No firearms; weapons. Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess a firearm or body armor. Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended and he may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.
